The paper focuses on the citation counting, citation ranking, and h-index of human-computer interaction (HCI) researchers, which falls under the sub-categories of digital libraries (cs.DL), human-computer interaction (cs.HC), information retrieval (cs.IR), cryptography and security (cs.CR), and databases (cs.DB). The study compares two databases, Scopus and Web of Science, which are commonly used in these sub-fields. Therefore, these five sub-categories are the most likely ones for this paper.
